    </node>
    <node id="claim:0008">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Epic CER bookmarks follow heading hierarchy (first, second, third, fourth level)</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "This is the epic type CR. And then you get Oracle and you get a few others, but the epic ones are usually if they are bookmarked, they are bookmarked according to the headings.", "ts": 609.0, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "So you'll, you'll get your first level heading, second level heading, second level heading. These are obviously third, second, third, third, fourth, et cetera.", "ts": 620.1, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d20">Epic-type CER documents are bookmarked according to their heading hierarchy (first through fourth level headings), though not every heading level is always bookmarked.</data>
      <data key="d21">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d22">[]</data>
      <data key="d23">fact</data>
      <data key="d24">False</data>
      <data key="d25">609.0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0009">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">MedBrief does not classify or date sections within CER documents</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "any computerized electronic records, when it goes into docs sort of, we don't do anything with it. We just classify it as a computerized electronic record. We do not date it. We do not even try to classify the sections within the documents at all.", "ts": 726.6, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d20">MedBrief's DocSorter process classifies CER documents as a whole type but does not date them or classify sections within them, because multiple clinical sections can appear on a single page.</data>
      <data key="d21">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d22">[]</data>
      <data key="d23">fact</data>
      <data key="d24">False</data>
      <data key="d25">726.6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0010">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Annotations are lost if a sorted set of records is subsequently updated</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "with annotations, the moment a client applies annotations, especially to a sorted set of records, if that sorted set of records get updated, meaning it needs to go back to docs or they need to insert more pages because the trust or hospital sent us more pages for whatever reason, then those annotations that they make is lost.", "ts": 815.4, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d20">Any annotations a client applies to a sorted set of records are permanently lost if the records need to be updated (e.g., new pages inserted).</data>
      <data key="d21">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d22">[]</data>
      <data key="d23">fact</data>
      <data key="d24">False</data>
      <data key="d25">815.4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0011">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Redaction would also be lost on record update, and it is not yet implemented</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "it's not something that has been implemented yet, but if we do implement it, it would be a reduction. Once we implement reduction, reduction would also be lost if the sorted records get updated.", "ts": 841.9, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d20">Redaction has not yet been implemented. If it is implemented, it will face the same loss-on-update problem as annotations.</data>
      <data key="d21">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d22">[]</data>
      <data key="d23">fact</data>
      <data key="d24">False</data>
      <data key="d25">841.9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0012">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Annotation visibility can be scoped to self, firm, or no one</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "the user can add annotations. They can also choose who the annotation should be visible to. Should it be visible to no one or to just themselves or to everybody in their firm?", "ts": 888.8, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d20">Users can control the visibility of annotations: private (no one), self-only, or all members of their firm.</data>
      <data key="d21">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d22">[]</data>
      <data key="d23">fact</data>
      <data key="d24">False</data>
      <data key="d25">888.8</data>
