    <node id="question:0010">
      <data key="d0">Question</data>
      <data key="d1">What is the purpose of key events and who uses them?</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "what purpose does the key events, like, let's say we could generate key events either with chronologies on a case or no chronologies. Like, who wants to see those? Why do they want to see them? And what use are the key events to somebody?", "ts": 2115.6, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:08"]</data>
      <data key="d37">What is the purpose of the key events feature and who are the intended users?</data>
      <data key="d38">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d39">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d40">True</data>
      <data key="d41">Key events provides a lighter, lower-cost overview of the timeline of events in a matter, positioned between having nothing and paying for a full chronology, also responding to competitive pressure from AI legal document providers.</data>
      <data key="d42">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d43">2131.8</data>
      <data key="d44">info_seeking</data>
      <data key="d25">2115.6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="question:0011">
      <data key="d0">Question</data>
      <data key="d1">Who creates the Figma designs for MedBrief?</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "Who does these Figma? Designs, by the way.", "ts": 2242.3, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:08"]</data>
      <data key="d37">Who is responsible for the Figma design mockups shown?</data>
      <data key="d38">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d39">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d40">True</data>
      <data key="d41">Anna, a freelancer engaged half-day three times a week.</data>
      <data key="d42">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d43">2246.5</data>
      <data key="d44">info_seeking</data>
      <data key="d25">2242.3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="question:0012">
      <data key="d0">Question</data>
      <data key="d1">Does the ECA progress indicator track which wizard questions have been answered?</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "So that early case assessment on the dashboard there had like a progress thing. So does that progress through which of those questions on that page you've answered?", "ts": 2459.6, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:09"]</data>
      <data key="d37">Does the progress indicator shown on the ECA dashboard record represent progress through the individual wizard questions?</data>
      <data key="d38">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d39">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d40">True</data>
      <data key="d41">No. The status indicates the workflow stage (allocated, ready for QA, QA'd, uploaded and released), not which questions have been answered.</data>
      <data key="d42">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d43">2468.6</data>
      <data key="d44">clarifying</data>
      <data key="d25">2459.6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="question:0013">
      <data key="d0">Question</data>
      <data key="d1">Why did MedBrief move from Orthanc to Medream?</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "Do you know why we moved from Orthanc onto, what was it called? Medream.", "ts": 2617.3, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:10"]</data>
      <data key="d37">Why did MedBrief migrate the radiology viewer from Orthanc to Medream?</data>
      <data key="d38">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d39">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d40">True</data>
      <data key="d41">Primarily broader radiology format support — Orthanc could not read many data formats. Medream also supports PDF radiology reports inside the viewer.</data>
      <data key="d42">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d43">2624.8</data>
      <data key="d44">info_seeking</data>
      <data key="d25">2617.3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="question:0014">
      <data key="d0">Question</data>
      <data key="d1">How do clients find experts without MedBrief Match?</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "How do our clients find experts otherwise?", "ts": 2933.6, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:11"]</data>
      <data key="d37">How do MedBrief clients currently find medical experts without using MedBrief Match?</data>
      <data key="d38">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d39">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d40">True</data>
      <data key="d41">Clients either use their own list of previously-used experts or go through an expert agency, which can charge 20–45% markup on the expert's fee.</data>
      <data key="d42">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d43">2940.6</data>
      <data key="d44">info_seeking</data>
      <data key="d25">2933.6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="question:0015">
      <data key="d0">Question</data>
      <data key="d1">Does MedBrief Match show similar-case results in the UI?</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "And you also show them here or do you show them?", "ts": 3244.4, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:12"]</data>
      <data key="d37">Does MedBrief Match surface similar-case information to the user in the results view?</data>
      <data key="d38">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d39">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d40">True</data>
      <data key="d41">Yes. The total similar-case count is shown on the expert card across all Match matters; case details are shown only for the client's own matters.</data>
      <data key="d42">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d43">3246.6</data>
      <data key="d44">clarifying</data>
      <data key="d25">3244.4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="question:0016">
      <data key="d0">Question</data>
      <data key="d1">Could matters without sufficient info still allow browsing experts by speciality?</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "I imagine it would still be technically possible for, even if you had matters that didn't have any of those things and therefore you weren't able to generate backgrounds and recommended experts, it, it would still be useful for, for clients to just be able to like browse experts based on their own selection of speciality and just find people and pay.", "ts": 3718, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:13"]</data>
      <data key="d37">Could matters without sufficient information for MedBrief Match still allow clients to browse and shortlist experts manually by selecting their own speciality?</data>
      <data key="d38">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d39">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d40">True</data>
      <data key="d41">Not at the moment. If a matter lacks sufficient information, MedBrief Match is disabled. The page displays with an 'insufficient information' message. Chantel acknowledged it should theoretically be possible to browse independently, but this feature does not exist yet.</data>
      <data key="d42">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d45">3747</data>
      <data key="d44">info_seeking</data>
      <data key="d26">3718</data>
    </node>
    <node id="question:0017">
      <data key="d0">Question</data>
      <data key="d1">Is the entire search-to-response process end-to-end within MedBrief?</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "So does the whole process end to end, like the searching for them, sending the letter of approach, does this all happen within MedBrief? And then the person gets their email, the expert gets their email, they log into MedBrief, they can see the letter, and then they can, uh, they can accept or decline within, within MedBrief.", "ts": 4145, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:14"]</data>
      <data key="d37">Is the entire process from searching for an expert, sending the letter of approach, and the expert accepting or declining all handled within MedBrief, facilitated by system-generated emails?</data>
      <data key="d38">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d39">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d40">True</data>
      <data key="d41">Correct. Chantel confirmed the entire workflow is on-platform with system-generated emails.</data>
      <data key="d42">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d45">4167</data>
      <data key="d44">clarifying</data>
      <data key="d26">4145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="question:0018">
      <data key="d0">Question</data>
      <data key="d1">Is the letter of instruction also created inside the platform like the letter of approach?</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "Sorry, Chantelle, the letter of instruction, is that also created inside the platform here in a similar way to creating the letter of approach or is that different?", "ts": 4601, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:15"]</data>
      <data key="d37">Is the letter of instruction created inside the MedBrief platform in a similar manner to the letter of approach?</data>
      <data key="d38">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d39">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d40">True</data>
      <data key="d41">No. The letter of instruction is different and is not yet created inside the platform. It is planned for the future. Clients currently generate it themselves and attach it manually.</data>
      <data key="d42">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d45">4610</data>
      <data key="d44">info_seeking</data>
      <data key="d26">4601</data>
    </node>
    <node id="question:0019">
      <data key="d0">Question</data>
      <data key="d1">How does a disclosure get to the recipient — is it handled by MedBrief staff or is it automatic?</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d37">So does that mean, so does that come in, is there somebody then at MedBrief who handles these disclosures? Like they'll get notified and then they like send, send it to them? Or does it automatic? How does it, how does the disclosure get to the recipient?</data>
      <data key="d38">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d39">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d40">True</data>
      <data key="d41">Recipients receive an email. Existing MedBrief users get a direct login link; new users are asked to activate their profile. MedBrief staff are not needed unless there is an issue — it is automated.</data>
      <data key="d42">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d45">5387</data>
      <data key="d44">info_seeking</data>
      <data key="d26">5372</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "is there somebody then at MedBrief who handles these disclosures? Like they'll get notified and then they like send it to them? Or does it automatic?", "ts": 5372, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:17"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:01">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Records page permission model: super-admin, expert and client folder views</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:01"]</data>
      <data key="d46">1</data>
      <data key="d47">Recap of the records page, how personal folders are created under both case documentation and private folders, and what super-admins, experts and clients each see. Covers the parked project to rename private folders to workspace and group users by internal, client and expert.</data>
      <data key="d48">3.22</data>
      <data key="d49">249.32</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:02">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Unsorted records folder, client uploads and folder actions</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:02"]</data>
      <data key="d46">2</data>
      <data key="d47">The unsorted records folder where client-uploaded records land, the duplication this causes for the ops team, and folder actions such as rename, delete, download and notify. Includes the suppressed-invitation case where notification is replaced by sending the invitation.</data>
      <data key="d48">249.32</data>
      <data key="d49">411.8</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:03">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Records viewer (Apryse), CER bookmarks and the annotation/redaction problem</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d46">3</data>
      <data key="d47">The Apryse (formerly PDFTron) records viewer: bookmark and heading navigation of long computerised electronic records, why MedBrief does not classify or date CER sections, and the annotations and redaction feature. Explains how updates lose annotations and Dion's granular-storing project to preserve coordinates across page changes.</data>
      <data key="d48">411.8</data>
      <data key="d49">943.24</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:04">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">MedBrief Insights AI panel and Ask Alex mode</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:04"]</data>
      <data key="d46">4</data>
      <data key="d47">Introduction to the in-development MedBrief Insights AI panel and its primary Ask Alex mode for interrogating MedBrief-sorted records, with file and folder filters, example questions, references and a feedback mechanism. Notes the chat interface was built in-house and the AI team is still reviewing model accuracy.</data>
      <data key="d48">943.24</data>
      <data key="d49">1175.7</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:05">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">CER index mode: heading extraction, date and keyword filtering</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:05"]</data>
      <data key="d46">5</data>
      <data key="d47">The reworked CER index that extracts Epic bookmarks or, failing that, headings via a visual language model, presented as an interactive index with date-range and keyword filtering over heading content. Covers patient versus event sections, date-extraction rules per event type, and the decision to launch on Epic first as it is roughly 70% of CER records.</data>
      <data key="d48">1175.7</data>
      <data key="d49">1770.04</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:06">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Records date-range filter on files and documents</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:06"]</data>
      <data key="d46">6</data>
      <data key="d47">How the records-page date range works: each document and folder carries a date range from DocSorter, but the filter currently applies at file level rather than to documents within a file. Dion is to extend it to filter documents inside files, and any applied date range auto-carries into Ask Alex.</data>
      <data key="d48">1770.04</data>
      <data key="d49">1926.36</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:07">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Key events mode and the planned chronology wizard</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:07"]</data>
      <data key="d46">7</data>
      <data key="d47">The key events mode that lists a timeline of key events from the records, and why it is hard to do accurately. Covers the plan to build a chronology wizard so clinicians generate chronologies in MedBrief as a hyperlinked digital form rather than in Word, which would later feed key events.</data>
      <data key="d48">1926.36</data>
      <data key="d49">2075.86</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:08">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Key events positioning versus paid chronologies, and Figma mockups</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:08"]</data>
      <data key="d46">8</data>
      <data key="d47">Why key events exists as a lighter overview sitting between nothing and a paid chronology, framed against competition from AI legal-document providers and the cost of a full chronology. Reviews Figma designs by freelancer Anna for the key events view and the updated CER index.</data>
      <data key="d48">2075.86</data>
      <data key="d49">2328.04</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:09">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Early Case Assessment wizard</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:09"]</data>
      <data key="d46">9</data>
      <data key="d47">The ECA wizard that moved early case assessments from Word onto the platform, with structured questions on breach of duty and causation whose answers determine a supportive, not supportive or inconclusive conclusion. Notes that storing ECA data in the database makes it reusable by the AI team, for example for MedBrief Match.</data>
      <data key="d48">2328.04</data>
      <data key="d49">2532.54</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:10">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Radiology viewer migration from Orthanc to Medream</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:10"]</data>
      <data key="d46">10</data>
      <data key="d47">The radiology viewer, demonstrated in production, and the move from Orthanc to Medream. The main driver was broader format support, plus the ability to read PDF radiology reports inside the viewer, alongside study loading and measurement features.</data>
      <data key="d48">2532.54</data>
      <data key="d49">2675.96</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:11">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">MedBrief Match: expert-matching concept and enablement</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:11"]</data>
      <data key="d46">11</data>
      <data key="d47">Introduction to MedBrief Match (Medream Merge) for finding experts, currently live for select Lime users only, with enablement conditions such as matter-wizard creation and clinical-negligence cases. Covers AI-generated expert profiles sourced from the internet, the letter-of-approach approach, the cost advantage over expert agencies, and AI-recommended specialities and queries.</data>
      <data key="d48">2675.96</data>
      <data key="d49">3152.46</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:12">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">MedBrief Match results, similar-case matching and expert profiles</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:12"]</data>
      <data key="d46">12</data>
      <data key="d47">The expert search results grouped by speciality, including similar-case matching that cross-references the matter against other MedBrief Match matters. Walks through profile cards, hourly rate and turnaround data, filters, and AI-generated recommendation reasons for each expert.</data>
      <data key="d48">3152.46</data>
      <data key="d49">3482.5</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:13">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Generating and sending the letter of approach</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:13"]</data>
      <data key="d46">13</data>
      <data key="d47">Creating a letter of approach: standard template, the choice to show the claimant's full name or initials, AI-generated background and records of tape, attachments requested by Lime, and the criteria for sufficient matter information. The PDF is encrypted and viewed only after the expert logs in rather than sent as an attachment.</data>
      <data key="d48">3482.5</data>
      <data key="d49">3989.7</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:14">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Expert experience: messages page, user simulation and responding to a letter of approach</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:14"]</data>
      <data key="d46">14</data>
      <data key="d47">The new messages navigation item and how a super-admin can simulate an expert user to see what they receive. Walks through the expert responding to a letter of approach with the eight client questions, the accept, decline or request-more-information flow, mandatory terms and conditions, and profile confirmation.</data>
      <data key="d48">3989.7</data>
      <data key="d49">4449.8</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:15">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Letter of instruction, email-reply gap and billing automation plans</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:15"]</data>
      <data key="d46">15</data>
      <data key="d47">What happens after acceptance: the letter of instruction (created outside the platform for now), the manual handling of experts who reply by email, and the plan to invite the expert directly from the match page so the instructed status is captured. Also covers planned record-upload prompts to track report and invoice submission and automated billing service requests.</data>
      <data key="d48">4449.8</data>
      <data key="d49">4974.88</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:16">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Inviting users and experts, roles and suppressed invitations</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:16"]</data>
      <data key="d46">16</data>
      <data key="d47">Inviting users from the users page, how suggestions only appear for people with prior dealings with the client, and the available roles including expert, view-only expert, scanner and matter project manager. Demonstrates suppressing an invitation to pre-create an expert folder and the planned MedBrief Match marker on contacted experts.</data>
      <data key="d48">4974.88</data>
      <data key="d49">5184.4</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:17">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Disclosures: inter-party record sharing</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:17"]</data>
      <data key="d46">17</data>
      <data key="d47">Disclosures, where one firm discloses records and radiology to an opposing firm, created through a client-managed wizard with a fee whose liability can fall on either firm. Covers recipient access by email or activation, the 30-day expiry with reactivation, and updating the disclosed record set.</data>
      <data key="d48">5184.4</data>
      <data key="d49">5620.06</data>
      <data key="d50">[]</data>
      <data key="d51">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:18">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Communications tab and workflow-driving reports</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:18"]</data>
      <data key="d46">18</data>
      <data key="d47">The admin-only communications tab that links emails to a matter via reference number or records request, and the reports section that drives the ops team's workflow. Saved reports such as records-request daily chases, batches, clinical reports and new matter requests determine and track outstanding work.</data>
      <data key="d48">5620.06</data>
